			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2015</a> paper:</span><br><i>Analysis and transformation with the nuthatch tree-walking library</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AnyaHeleneBagge.html">Anya Helene Bagge</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2814251.2814264">10.1145/2814251.2814264</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3f.html"><span class="tagM">T3F: API</span></a><ul><li> Nuthatch is presented as a reusable library/API for tree traversal, analysis, and rewriting.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> Its core capabilities include specifying and executing transformations/rewrites over trees.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> A primary application is program analysis by traversing and collecting information from trees.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> As a software library for language processing, it supports building language engineering tooling.
</li></ul></li></ul>
